column2: what does the federal reserve do
column3: The Federal Reserve System ( also known as the Federal Reserve , and informally as the Fed ) is the central banking system of the United States .

column2: what does the federal reserve do
column3: It was created on December 23 , 1913 , with the enactment of the Federal Reserve Act , largely in response to a series of financial panics , particularly a severe panic in 1907 .

column2: what does the federal reserve do
column3: Over time , the roles and responsibilities of the Federal Reserve System have expanded and its structure has evolved .

column2: what does the federal reserve do
column3: Events such as the Great Depression were major factors leading to changes in the system .

column2: what does the federal reserve do
column3: The US Congress established three key objectives for monetary policy in the Federal Reserve Act : Maximum employment , stable prices , and moderate long-term interest rates .

column2: what does the federal reserve do
column3: The first two objectives are sometimes referred to as the Federal Reserve 's dual mandate .

column2: what does the federal reserve do
column3: Its duties have expanded over the years , and today , according to official Federal Reserve documentation , include conducting the nation 's monetary policy , supervising and regulating banking institutions , maintaining the stability of the financial system and providing financial services to depository institutions , the U.S. government , and foreign official institutions .

column2: what does the federal reserve do
column3: The Fed also conducts research into the economy and releases numerous publications , such as the Beige Book .

column2: what does the federal reserve do
column3: The Federal Reserve System 's structure is composed of the presidentially appointed Board of Governors ( or Federal Reserve Board ) , the Federal Open Market Committee ( FOMC ) , twelve regional Federal Reserve Banks located in major cities throughout the nation , numerous privately owned U.S. member banks and various advisory councils .

column2: what does the federal reserve do
column3: The FOMC is the committee responsible for setting monetary policy and consists of all seven members of the Board of Governors and the twelve regional bank presidents , though only five bank presidents vote at any given time ( the president of the New York Fed and four others who rotate through one-year terms ) .

column2: what does the federal reserve do
column3: The Federal Reserve System has both private and public components , and was designed to serve the interests of both the general public and private bankers .

column2: what does the federal reserve do
column3: The result is a structure that is considered unique among central banks .

column2: what does the federal reserve do
column3: It is also unusual in that an entity outside of the central bank , namely the United States Department of the Treasury , creates the currency used .

column2: what does the federal reserve do
column3: According to the Board of Governors , the Federal Reserve System `` is considered an independent central bank because its monetary policy decisions do not have to be approved by the President or anyone else in the executive or legislative branches of government , it does not receive funding appropriated by the Congress , and the terms of the members of the Board of Governors span multiple presidential and congressional terms . ''

column2: what does the federal reserve do
column3: The authority of the Federal Reserve System is derived from statutes enacted by the U.S. Congress and the System is subject to congressional oversight .

column2: what does the federal reserve do
column3: The members of the Board of Governors , including its chairman and vice-chairman , are chosen by the President and confirmed by the Senate .

column2: what does the federal reserve do
column3: The government also exercises some control over the Federal Reserve by appointing and setting the salaries of the system 's highest-level employees .

column2: what does the federal reserve do
column3: Nationally chartered commercial banks are required to hold stock in the Federal Reserve Bank of their region ; this entitles them to elect some of the members of the board of the regional Federal Reserve Bank .

column2: what does the federal reserve do
column3: Thus the Federal Reserve system has both public and private aspects .

column2: what does the federal reserve do
column3: The U.S. Government receives all of the system 's annual profits , after a statutory dividend of 6 % on member banks ' capital investment is paid , and an account surplus is maintained .

column2: what does the federal reserve do
column3: In 2010 , the Federal Reserve made a profit of $ 82 billion and transferred $ 79 billion to the U.S. Treasury .

column2: what does the federal reserve do
column3: This was followed at the end of 2011 with a transfer of $ 77 billion in profits to the U.S. Treasury Department .

column2: what does judgment as a matter of law mean
column3: Judgment as a matter of law ( JMOL ) is a motion made by a party , during trial , claiming the opposing party has insufficient evidence to reasonably support its case .

column2: what does judgment as a matter of law mean
column3: JMOL is also known as a directed verdict , which it has replaced in American Federal courts .

column2: what does judgment as a matter of law mean
column3: JMOL is similar to judgment on the pleadings and summary judgment , all of which test the factual sufficiency of a claim .

column2: what does judgment as a matter of law mean
column3: Judgment on the pleadings is a motion made after pleading and before discovery ; summary judgment happens after discovery and before trial ; JMOL occurs during trial .

column2: what does judgment as a matter of law mean
column3: In United States federal courts , JMOL is a creation of Federal Rules of Civil Procedure Rule 50 .

column2: what does judgment as a matter of law mean
column3: JMOL is decided by the standard of whether a reasonable jury could find in favor of the party opposing the JMOL motion .

column2: what does judgment as a matter of law mean
column3: If there is no evidence to support a reasonable conclusion for the opposing party , judgment is entered by the court and the case is over .

column2: what does judgment as a matter of law mean
column3: If there is sufficient evidence to make a reasonable conclusion in favor of the opposing party , but there is equally strong evidence to support an opposite conclusion , the party with the burden of persuasion fails .

column2: what does judgment as a matter of law mean
column3: Timing is very important in making a motion for JMOL ; the motion can only be made once the opposing party has presented its case .

column2: what does judgment as a matter of law mean
column3: In civil cases , the plaintiff presents her case , then the defendant presents his/her case , then the plaintiff may present a rebuttal .

column2: what does judgment as a matter of law mean
column3: So , once the plaintiff has presented his/her case , the defendant may move for JMOL , but the plaintiff may not .

column2: what does judgment as a matter of law mean
column3: Once the defendant has finished presenting his/her case , the plaintiff may move for JMOL , and so may the defendant .

column2: what does judgment as a matter of law mean
column3: JMOL motions may also be made after the verdict is returned , where they are called `` renewed '' motions for judgment as a matter of law ( RJMOL ) , but the motion is still commonly known by its former name , judgment notwithstanding verdict , or j.n.o.v . ( from the English judgment and the Latin non obstante veredicto ) .

column2: what does judgment as a matter of law mean

column2: How Works Diaphragm Pump
column3: Diaphragm pump schematic .

column2: How Works Diaphragm Pump
column3: A diaphragm pump ( also known as a Membrane pump , Air Operated Double Diaphragm Pump ( AODD ) or Pneumatic Diaphragm Pump ) is a positive displacement pump that uses a combination of the reciprocating action of a rubber , thermoplastic or teflon diaphragm and suitable valves either side of the diaphragm ( check valve , butterfly valves , flap valves , or any other form of shut-off valves ) to pump a fluid .

column2: How Works Diaphragm Pump
column3: There are three main types of diaphragm pumps:

column2: How Works Diaphragm Pump
column3: Those in which the diaphragm is sealed with one side in the fluid to be pumped , and the other in air or hydraulic fluid .

column2: How Works Diaphragm Pump
column3: The diaphragm is flexed , causing the volume of the pump chamber to increase and decrease .

column2: How Works Diaphragm Pump
column3: A pair of non-return check valves prevent reverse flow of the fluid .

column2: How Works Diaphragm Pump
column3: Those employing volumetric positive displacement where the prime mover of the diaphragm is electro-mechanical , working through a crank or geared motor drive , or purely mechanical , such as with a lever or handle .

column2: How Works Diaphragm Pump
column3: This method flexes the diaphragm through simple mechanical action , and one side of the diaphragm is open to air .

column2: How Works Diaphragm Pump
column3: Those employing one or more unsealed diaphragms with the fluid to be pumped on both sides .

column2: How Works Diaphragm Pump
column3: The diaphragm ( s ) again are flexed , causing the volume to change .

column2: How Works Diaphragm Pump
column3: When the volume of a chamber of either type of pump is increased ( the diaphragm moving up ) , the pressure decreases , and fluid is drawn into the chamber .

column2: How Works Diaphragm Pump
column3: When the chamber pressure later increases from decreased volume ( the diaphragm moving down ) , the fluid previously drawn in is forced out .

column2: How Works Diaphragm Pump
column3: Finally , the diaphragm moving up once again draws fluid into the chamber , completing the cycle .

column2: How Works Diaphragm Pump
column3: This action is similar to that of the cylinder in an internal combustion engine .

column2: where is the arctic circle located on the earth
column3: The Arctic Circle is the southernmost latitude in the Northern Hemisphere at which the sun can remain continuously above or below the horizon for 24 hours ( at the June solstice and December solstice respectively ) .

column2: where is the arctic circle located on the earth
column3: North of the Arctic Circle , the sun is above the horizon for 24 continuous hours at least once per year ( and therefore visible at midnight ) and below the horizon for 24 continuous hours at least once per year .

column2: where is the arctic circle located on the earth
column3: On the Arctic Circle those events occur , in principle , exactly once per year , at the June and December solstices , respectively .

column2: where is the arctic circle located on the earth

column2: where is the arctic circle located on the earth
column3: In fact , because of atmospheric refraction and mirages , and because the sun appears as a disk and not a point , part of the midnight sun may be seen on the night of the northern summer solstice up to about 50 ′ ( ) south of the Arctic Circle ; similarly , on the day of the northern winter solstice , part of the sun may be seen up to about 50′ north of the Arctic Circle .

column2: where is the arctic circle located on the earth
column3: That is true at sea level ; those limits increase with elevation above sea level although in mountainous regions , there is often no direct view of the true horizon .

column2: where is the arctic circle located on the earth

column2: where is the arctic circle located on the earth
column3: It directly depends on the Earth 's axial tilt , which fluctuates within a margin of 2° over a 40,000 year period , notably due to tidal forces resulting from the orbit of the Moon .
